The 2020-21 school year has already presented a number of exciting firsts for educator Qorsho Hassan — the first time beginning school in a completely new learning model, the first year in District 196 and the first Somali-American to earn the title of Minnesota Teacher of the Year.

And her top priorities as she begins her time at Echo Park Elementary School is "amplifying marginalized voices, advocating for equity and antiracism, and shedding light on the barriers to retaining teachers of color." We are thrilled to begin the new school year with the #MNTOY. #196Pride

The PayPAMS food and nutrition account management platform is live, and families can now set up their accounts. Meal account balances from the 2019-20 school year have automatically been transferred over to PayPAMS. Once your account setup is complete, it can take up to two days to see the available balance.

###

La plataforma de gestión de cuentas de alimentos y nutrición de PayPams ya está en funcionamiento, y las familias ya pueden configurar sus cuentas. Los balances de las cuentas de comida del año escolar 2019-20 han sido transferidos automáticamente a PayPams. Una vez que se haya completado la configuración de la cuenta, puede tomar hasta dos días para ver el saldo disponible.

###

Koontada cuntada iyo nafaqada ee loo yaqaan 'PayPAMS' waa mid nool, qoysaskuna hadda waa ay sameyn karaan akoonadooda. Hadhaaga xisaabta cuntada ee sanad dugsiyeedka 2019-20 si otomaatig ah ayaa loo wareejiyay. Mar haddii dejinta xisaabtaada la dhammaystiro, waxay qaadan kartaa ilaa laba maalmood in la arko dheelitirka jira.

Tonight the District 196 School Board approved a resolution adopting the 2020-21 Flexible Learning Plan, establishing a base learning model in which students will begin the school year in a hybrid scenario. The plan provides all students in-person learning opportunities two days each week and distance learning three days each week in alternating cohorts.

Read the formal resolution: https://bit.ly/3kxChWn

View the 2020-21 Flexible Learning Plan: https://bit.ly/31HoWC7

post_text:
District 196 is replacing FeePay with MyPaymentsPlus and PayPams. After August 3, FeePay will no longer be available to families.

MyPaymentsPlus will be used for online payments for athletics and activities registrations, field trips and fees. PayPams, which the district already uses for free and reduced-price lunch applications, will be used for managing student meal accounts, including online payments and meal account balances.

Community Education will continue to use Eleyo for program registration.

Families who would like to access documents in their FeePay accounts should do so before the August 3 shutdown. All available meal balances will be automatically transferred to the PayPams system. Refunds for activities should be requested through your school, as schools have access to FeePay until the August 30 sunset date.

Click the link below for more information.

The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) program is available to families who need assistance with access to food. P-EBT can provide families with children up to $325 for groceries. The Minnesota Department of Human Services says as many as 150,000 families may be eligible for these additional food assistance benefits.

What started as a small tutoring service for fellow classmates during distance learning, continues to grow into a larger effort to create "connexions" during the pandemic. Senior Ankitha Kumar and several of her Eagan High School peers launched Connexions Tutoring, a free tutoring service to anyone in need. There are now 12 tutors with a combined 600 hours of service to over 80 students.

"We want education to be 100% accessible. We don't want money or lack of transportation or anything to stop the students who need the help to be able to get the help," Kumar said. #196Pride

Each May, we formally celebrate the profession that is teaching and those who fill the role of educating the next generation. We’d like to stretch out Teacher Appreciation Week just a little bit longer with this video to celebrate the over 2,000 incredible educators in District 196.

In the last few months, you have had to radically change how you educate students. You recreated your classroom via Zoom and other digital means. You have gone above and beyond to build and enhance relationships with students, families and each other. You've discovered solutions to problems that you never thought you would have to deal with. Thank you! #196Pride #InThisTogether #TeacherAppreciation

In just elementary school, Cedar Park STEM Elementary students are GLOBALLY RECOGNIZED for their exceptional math skills following an outstanding showing at the Rookie Perennial Math international competition. Cedar Park's team, comprised of one third grader and 24 fourth graders, qualified by earning the top 25 scores on the qualifying test this past fall.

And seven students earned global recognition and the champion plaque, which places them in the top 10 percent of teams in the world! Congratulations to Cedar Park and Sarah Nanam Kumar, Aarav Chakrabarty, Shriya Rachakonda, Freedom Thompson, Aniella Volpano, Amir Essa and Taj Bora! #196Pride

Two District 196 STEM educators are putting their expertise and creativity to work in order to equip local health care workers with desperately needed personal protection equipment.

The fabrication labs, or Fab Labs, at Valley Middle School of STEM and Apple Valley High School - STEM are churning out face shields and face masks using 3D printers, which are then donated to local long-term care facilities and hospitals. Spearheaded by Chris Lee (AVHS) and Brian Martin (VMSS), together they have produced over 500 face shields and 200 face masks. #196Pride #InThisTogether

DISTRICT196.ORG
District 196 supports bonding request to fund Diffley Road improvements
text:
The District 196 School Board unanimously approved a resolution supporting Dakota County’s request is for $4.62 million to fund several proposed pedestrian and vehicle safety improvements on Diffley Road, Braddock Trail and the adjacent campuses of Northview Elementary School, Dakota Hills Middle School and Eagan High School.

The proposed improvements in the bonding bill include:

• Reconstruct Diffley from a four- to a two-lane road between Lexington Avenue to 2,000 feet east of Braddock Trail;
• Install roundabouts on Diffley at the intersections of Daniel Drive and Braddock Trail;
• Modify parking lot entrances/exits on Braddock Trail, and
• Construct a new road from the north side of the Daniel Drive roundabout into the high school south parking lot.

DISTRICT196.ORG
District 196 supports bonding request to fund Diffley Road improvements

The stadium lights at District 196 high schools illuminated empty fields last night in a show of support and encouragement for students, especially the Class of 2020. Our high schools are participating in the Be the Light campaign along with districts across the state. Every Monday at 8:20 p.m., for 20 minutes, stadium lights will be turned on.

“It really was extremely powerful,” said Eastview Athletics Director Matt Percival. “Just glad that 20 minutes of lights on gave some hope, some reassurance that this will all be OK. And when things do return to normal, whenever that may be, the lights will be on for them.”

#InThisTogether #196Pride

As distance learning gets under way across Minnesota, we are relying on our digital systems like never before.

Our Schoology and Seesaw learning management systems continue to experience outages and intermittent loading errors due to the significant increase in use of the platforms. The national Schoology and Seesaw support teams are monitoring the situation and working hard to minimize any disruptions to service to member districts.

Schools and teachers will be flexible with students during this time regarding assignments or attendance.

We will inform you if we experience a significant disruption in service, and ask for your patience and understanding for any disruptions that may occur. We have the following support structures in place for distance learning:

𝐂𝐥𝐚𝐬𝐬𝐫𝐨𝐨𝐦 𝐐𝐮𝐞𝐬𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧𝐬 𝐚𝐛𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐂𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐬𝐞𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤 (𝐢𝐧𝐜𝐥𝐮𝐝𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐒𝐞𝐞𝐬𝐚𝐰): Direct to the classroom teacher using email or Schoology Messages

An East Lake Elementary teacher turned to chalk to help spread positivity among her school community. Kristin Moore, who teaches fifth-grade, left messages of kindness and encouragement on driveways, including those of students and staff.

"I saw a teacher in another state post on Instagram that she did this and felt inspired! I wanted my students, and their families, to know that I am thinking about them and that we are all in this together."

She is pictured with fellow East Lake fifth-grade teacher Audrey Glogoza. Don't worry, she said, they were in separate cars and practiced appropriate social distancing.

"We just did this because we miss our students," she added. "Everything is uncertain right now, but our classroom and school community remain strong." #196Pride

IMPORTANT MESSAGE REGARDING COVID-19:

𝐃𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐫𝐢𝐜𝐭 𝟏𝟗𝟔 𝐰𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐜𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐞𝐥 𝐬𝐜𝐡𝐨𝐨𝐥 𝐛𝐞𝐠𝐢𝐧𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐌𝐨𝐧𝐝𝐚𝐲, 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐜𝐡 𝟏𝟔 𝐮𝐧𝐭𝐢𝐥 𝐌𝐨𝐧𝐝𝐚𝐲, 𝐌𝐚𝐫𝐜𝐡 𝟑𝟎.

In response to an executive order from Governor Walz regarding the novel coronavirus (COVID-19), District 196 will cancel school beginning Monday, March 16 until Monday, March 30. This includes all programs and activities. Teachers will not be providing instruction this week.

School buildings will be open Monday, March 16 from 7 a.m. to 6 p.m. for the limited purpose of allowing students/families and staff to collect necessary items. During this time, families can pick up student prescriptions, technology devices, additional bags of food and other items.

If necessary, we will implement our e-learning plan on or after March 30.

More information regarding e-learning, student services and a full list of canceled and scheduled programming will be provided later.

For more updates, visit our COVID-10 Information webpage at www.district196.org/about/coronavirus.

post_text:
Three District 196 middle school students earn shot at SCRIPPS National Spelling Bee bid

Three District 196 middle school students have qualified for the metro spelling bee in March and will be competing for an opportunity to represent Minnesota at the SCRIPPS National Spelling Bee in Washington D.C. in May.

The qualifiers are Kartik Saravanapandi of Black Hawk Middle School in Eagan, May Tang of Falcon Ridge Middle School in Apple Valley, and Rasin Hussain of Scott Highlands Middle School in Apple Valley.

Each of these students won their school spelling bee to earn the opportunity to take the qualifying exam online. Forty-three students total qualified for the Metropolitan Educational Cooperative Service Unit Spelling Bee, which will be held Tuesday, March 24, 5:30 p.m., at the Shoreview Community Center. The winner earns a trip to the national bee in D.C. #196Pride

post_text: Eagan High School junior Kennedi Orr defended her title and was once again named the Minnesota Gatorade Volleyball Player of the Year! Kennedi, a setter and outside hitter, recorded 405 assists, 242 kills and 204 digs during the 2019 high school season. She shined in the Class AAA state championship match and led the Wildcats to a 31-1 season. Kennedi played with Team USA this fall and won gold at the FIVB Girls U18 World Championships in Egypt. She is an exemplary member of the District 196 community and we are incredibly proud! Congratulations, Kennedi! #196Pride

post_text:
We celebrated a lot of great things during last night's School Board meeting, including the well-deserved retirement of longtime board member Bob Schutte and we welcomed new board member Cory Johnson! Incumbent board members Jackie Magnuson, Joel Albright and Sachin Isaacs were also sworn in.

Bob Schutte served from 1987-1993 and 1999-2019. During his time on the board, enrollment grew from 17,000 students to 30,000 students, and the district opened 16 schools! We are grateful for Bob's unwavering support and advocacy of our students, teachers and district. Thank you for your service!

Incoming board member Cory Johnson is a parent to two students in District 196, a military veteran and is passionate about public education. We are thrilled to welcome him to our team! #196Pride

post_text:
A districtwide communication was sent this morning regarding the continued issues with FeePay. We are aware of families’ continued issues with the FeePay system as it remains offline while updating. This includes the inability to login, complete meal account fund deposits, sign up for activities and reset passwords.

For families who cannot access FeePay for meal fund deposits, your student will never be denied a meal. They will have access to school lunch but not a la carte menu items. During this time, students can bring cash or a check as well.

We have been in regular communication with Sourcewell, the company that owns FeePay, and will notify families when the system is back online. We apologize for the inconvenience and we appreciate your patience during this time.

The District 196 School Board approved revisions to the 2020-21 academic calendar, which now includes two days off school, Thursday, Oct. 15 and Friday Oct. 16, for the Minnesota Educators Academy (MEA) conference.

Last year, the board approved a calendar that did not include the traditional days off school for MEA due to uncertainty at the time about the future of the conference. Following Education Minnesota's decision to continue the conference, and with input from stakeholders, administration recommended reinstating the days as no school. Read more and download the revised calendar. #196Pride

post_text:
Schools across District 196 opened their doors today to local servicemen and women and showered them with gratitude in honor of Veterans Day. The all-school assembly at Highland Elementary has been going strong since 1986 when Duane Burns, the first principal of the school and Vietnam veteran, first started the event.

Both Eagan and Apple Valley high schools held ceremonies that included ROTC students and guest speakers. Rosemount Elementary hosted a social hour for local vets. And Falcon Ridge Middle School Festival Choir, directed by Michael Skaar, sang the National Anthem at the unveiling of a new veterans marker at Shadow Falls Park in St. Paul. Check out more photos from the day. https://flic.kr/s/aHsmJj8poh Thank you all for your service! 🇺🇸 #196Pride #VeteransDay

Enrollment in a District 196 magnet school for the 2020-21 school year is now accepting applications. Families must submit an application by Jan. 8 to be considered for one of the five elementary magnet schools and by Feb. 12 for Valley Middle School of STEM.

Our magnet schools offer parents increased choice in their child’s education by providing a concentrated focus that offers innovative ways to meet students’ learning goals through a particular theme. post_text:
In conjunction with National School Bus Safety Week, we are celebrating our dedicated crew of District 196 transportation folks! We are excited to celebrate Transportation Employees Appreciate Week in recognition of the excellent work they do each and every day. District 196 has the largest school district-owned bus fleet in the state. Nearly 300 committed employees ensure our 227 vehicles are running and transport students safely.

Fun facts: Together, they travel 2.9 million miles each year, transporting more than 23,000 students twice every school day, to and from more than 5,500 bus stops throughout the district.

Thank you, transportation employees! #196Pride

post_text: It has been an incredible season for Eastview High School's AJ Green, who was recently named the 2019 Minnesota Gatorade boys' track and field Player of the Year! His season included an incredible showing in the 800-meter race both locally and nationally. He set a state record in the 800 at the Section 3AA Championships, followed by a state title in the same race and took first at the prestigious Brooks PR Invitational in Seattle. To cap off the year, he captured fourth place at the USATF U20 National Championships! Outside of running, AJ is an outstanding scholar and volunteer in his community. He truly embodies #196Pride in all he does. Congratulations!

post_text: For the fifth year in a row, Eagan High School was named one of the top-10 Schools of Outstanding Distinction and Apple Valley and Eastview high schools were two of the top-20 Speech Schools of Excellence at the National Speech and Debate Tournament June 16-21 in Dallas. Apple Valley students and coaches (pictured) also brought home the tournament’s top trophy, the Bruno E. Jacob Award, for winning the greatest number of cumulative rounds in main events at the national tournament. The speech and debate program in District 196 continues to be an incredible powerhouse and we are so proud of the accomplishments this year! Congratulations! #196Pride
